ect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/303338747\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Peter Whittenberger is an interdisciplinary media artist and educator whose work explores contemporary definitions of self in relationship to the greater human narrative. Whittenberger is most interested in exploring how the landscape can serve as a network containing the data of the history of various species. Whittenberger holds a BFA in printmaking from the University of Montana and an MFA in interdisciplinary art from the University of Nevada, Reno. Whittenberger has shown his work in the FILE Festival, Supernova Digital Animation Festival, the Athens Animfest, the 2-Minute Film Festival at the Carnegie Museum of Art, and many others across Europe, North America, Africa, Asia, and South America. Outside of his studio, Whittenberger owns a boutique dog grooming salon with his wife Andi in Reno, NV and serves as an Adjunct Instructor at Truckee Meadows Community College.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','A Desert Network: Lake Tahoe to Pyramid Lake','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2018-12-05 04:15:50','2018-12-05 04:15:50','',179,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(184,11,'2018-12-05 04:20:23','2018-12-05 04:20:23','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://lisamoren.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew (opens in a new tab)\">Lisa Moren</a>, <a href=\"http://www.ne-ja.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Neja Tomsic</a>, <a href=\"http://www.baraga.net/\" target=\"_blank\">Martin Baraga</a> and <a href=\"http://www.enginesofthefuture.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Jaimes Mayhew</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"191,192,195,197\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"NONUMENT 01:: McKeldin Fountain is Baltimores virtual monument located in the Inner Harbor and free speech zone.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In opposition to bronze and stone, the nonument or no monument recreates the destroyed Brutalist-style monument the City of Baltimore and private partners tore down in January 2017. installs new and emerging media forms in order to capture the transitory significance of everyday experiences. We seek to honor hidden urban spaces that carry symbolic value for ordinary people.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By using this app, anyone can put back the fountain and experience first-hand memories from ordinary activities, art events and protests, including uprisings following the death of Freddie Gray, Peace Vigils, LGBTQ issues and Occupy Baltimore.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When viewers hold up a mobile device like a protest sign, the participant will put back the fountain with 18 animated waterfalls including an infamous double waterfall. Viewers will see and hear documented interviews that includes a diversity of Baltimore voices from a former Mayor and ACLU lawyer to rappers, teachers and protestors, including the Women In Black who stood for peace at the site every Friday since December 2001. Whisper Chambers inside the fountain offer underrepresented voices in Baltimore City that are often unheard but significant to the vibrant life of any urban environment.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The story of McKeldin Fountain is part of the escalating privatization of public spaces worldwide, a trend that continues to diminish access to full participation and free speech for ordinary people in everyday urban life. This socially engaged intervention is an ambitious take on the latest AR technology in order to address the politics of reclaiming public space including: how public behavior is controlled by a variety of mechanisms? and, who has more exclusive access to what spaces?&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This augmented reality public art project is free to download to your phone.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://nonument01.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"http://nonument01.org (opens in a new tab)\">http://nonument01.org</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/303771421\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/303771421\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Acknowledgments</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Artists: Lisa Moren, Director and Lead Production; Jaimes Mayhew, Co-Production;Martin Bricelj Baraga and Neja Tomi, NONUMENT founders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Software coding and app development by <strong>Balti-Virtual</strong><br>Sound Score by <strong>Erik Spangler</strong> with Whisper Chambers by <strong>JMoney fur</strong><br>Interviews by <strong>Lisa Moren</strong><br>Interview editing by <strong>Jaimes Mayhew</strong> with audio engineering by <strong>Lexie Mountain</strong><br>Artist Audio Tour by <strong>Lisa Moren</strong> with audio engineering by <strong>Timothy Nohe</strong><br>3D models by <strong>Ben Shaffer</strong>, and by <strong>Ryan Zuber</strong>, IRC at UMBC.<br>The 3D printed model was printed by the good folks at the <strong>Digital Harbor Foundation</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This project grateful for the generous support from the Saul Zaentz Innovation Fund in Film + Media at Johns Hopkins University.&nbsp;We are also grateful for support from The Andy Warhol Foundation for The Visual Arts, The Grit Fund, Baltimore Women and Tech, and the Imaging Research Center and CAHSSat UMBC.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Special thanks to for the expertise of Audrey Ewall, Fred Scharmen, Mike Schector and the Saul Zaentz Incubation Team. We appreciate the dedicated support from MoTA Museum, Baltimore Visitors Center, D-Center and Maryland Art Place who support this project in so many flexible ways.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NONUMENT 01::McKeldin Fountain','','publish','closed','open','','nonument-01mckeldin-fountain','','\nhttps://vimeo.com/303771421','2018-12-07 16:32:17','2018-12-07 16:32:17','',0,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/?p=184',0,'post','',0),(190,1,'2018-12-05 04:20:23','2018-12-05 04:20:23','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;Artist Statement Text&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &lt;Project Website URL&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;Video Documentation Text&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&lt;Artist Bio Text&gt;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NONUMENT 01::McKeldin Fountain','','inherit','closed','closed','','184-revision-v1','','','2018-12-05 04:20:23','2018-12-05 04:20:23','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/184-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(191,1,'2018-12-05 04:20:53','2018-12-05 04:20:53','','Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','lisa-moren-neja-tomsic-martin-baraga-and-jaimes-mayhew-1','','','2018-12-05 04:20:53','2018-12-05 04:20:53','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Lisa-Moren-Neja-Tomsic-Martin-Baraga-and-Jaimes-Mayhew-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(192,1,'2018-12-05 04:20:55','2018-12-05 04:20:55','','Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew 2','','inherit','closed','closed','','lisa-moren-neja-tomsic-martin-baraga-and-jaimes-mayhew-2','','','2018-12-05 04:20:55','2018-12-05 04:20:55','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Lisa-Moren-Neja-Tomsic-Martin-Baraga-and-Jaimes-Mayhew-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(212,1,'2018-12-05 04:38:08','2018-12-05 04:38:08','','Snow Yunxue Fu 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','snow-yunxue-fu-1','','','2018-12-05 04:38:08','2018-12-05 04:38:08','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Snow-Yunxue-Fu-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(194,1,'2018-12-05 04:20:59','2018-12-05 04:20:59','','Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew 3','','inherit','closed','closed','','lisa-moren-neja-tomsic-martin-baraga-and-jaimes-mayhew-3','','','2018-12-05 04:20:59','2018-12-05 04:20:59','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Lisa-Moren-Neja-Tomsic-Martin-Baraga-and-Jaimes-Mayhew-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(195,1,'2018-12-05 04:21:02','2018-12-05 04:21:02','','Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew 4','','inherit','closed','closed','','lisa-moren-neja-tomsic-martin-baraga-and-jaimes-mayhew-4','','','2018-12-05 04:21:02','2018-12-05 04:21:02','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Lisa-Moren-Neja-Tomsic-Martin-Baraga-and-Jaimes-Mayhew-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(208,1,'2018-12-05 04:32:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','closed','open','','','','','2018-12-05 04:32:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/?p=208',0,'post','',0),(398,1,'2018-12-06 00:20:06','2018-12-06 00:20:06','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://www.kairus.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Andreas Zingerle and Linda Kronman</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery link=\"none\" ids=\"155,156,157,158\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Megacorp.\" is a corporate conglomerate inspired by its equally powerful counterparts in science fiction. The artwork is based on a collection of fake websites scraped from <g class=\"gr_ gr_12 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Grammar only-ins replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"12\" data-gr-id=\"12\">internet</g> by the artist duo KairUs. These companies exist only virtually and are used by cyber criminals for phishing attacks or to support scam stories. The \"Megacorp.\" exists therefore as an umbrella company for subsidiary companies that are 100% dummy cooperations. \"Megacorp.\" operates on a global scale and is constantly growing with firms represented in almost every branch of industry. The strategic objectives according to the \"Megacorp.\" <g class=\"gr_ gr_14 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Grammar only-ins doubleReplace replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"14\" data-gr-id=\"14\">Mission</g> statement is to: \"offer complete services from one source which can serve the entire market\". <g class=\"gr_ gr_15 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Punctuation only-ins replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"15\" data-gr-id=\"15\">Accordingly</g> the subsidiary companies cover domestic and international export, real estate agents, insurance companies, law firms, security companies, banks, educational institutions, hospitals, online commerce, economic communities <g class=\"gr_ gr_16 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Punctuation only-ins replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"16\" data-gr-id=\"16\">and</g> ministries<g class=\"gr_ gr_19 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Style replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"19\" data-gr-id=\"19\">.The</g> functions of \"Megacorp.\" are presented in the form of an interim report and company visuals. By examining the fake websites the artwork reflects both the imaginary and the real world \'megacorps\', questioning centralization of power.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Written Document</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:file {\"id\":222,\"href\":\"https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Andreas-Zingerle-and-Linda-Kronman-Paper.pdf\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-file\"><a href=\"https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Andreas-Zingerle-and-Linda-Kronman-Paper.pdf\">Andreas Zingerle and Linda Kronman - Paper</a><a href=\"https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Andreas-Zingerle-and-Linda-Kronman-Paper.pdf\" class=\"wp-block-file__button\" download>Download</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:file -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://megacorp.kairus.org\" target=\"_blank\">http://megacorp.kairus.org</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/303156442\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/303156442\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>KairUs is a collective of two artists Linda Kronman (Finland) and Andreas Zingerle (Austria). Currently based in Daejeon (Republic of Korea), they explore topics such as vulnerabilities in IoT devices, corporatization of city governance in Smart Cities and citizen sensitive projects in which technology is used to reclaim control of our living environments. Their practice based research is closely intertwined with their artistic production, adopting methodologies used by anthropologists and sociologist, their artworks are often informed by archival research, participation observations and field research. Besides the artworks they publish academic research papers and open access publications to contextualize their artworks to wider discourses such as data privacy &amp; security, activism &amp; hacking culture, disruptive art practices, electronic waste and materiality of the internet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Tracking evil businesses   The Megacorp. Business conglomerate','','inherit','closed','closed','','154-revision-v1','','','2018-12-06 00:20:06','2018-12-06 00:20:06','',154,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/154-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(210,1,'2018-12-05 04:36:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','closed','open','','','','','2018-12-05 04:36:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/?p=210',0,'post','',0),(211,13,'2018-12-05 04:43:13','2018-12-05 04:43:13','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"https://snowyunxuefu.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"Snow Yunxue Fu (opens in a new tab)\">Snow Yunxue Fu</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"212,213,214,215,216,217\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Karst is a liminal space in between the representational and the theatrical, the limited and the multi-dimensional, and the abstract and the real all meeting together.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Inspired from Fu\'s childhood experience visiting the caves from her hometown in Southwest China. The memories and the impact of the experience is still quite vivid. The space felt both extremely claustrophobic and large, and this aspect would be evident especially when the viewers are experiencing the piece within the VR Headset, as the ceiling of the cave is about 60 feet high (something you will definitely experience less in this recorded video). The rock shapes in the virtual scene are made with fluid simulation software Realflow, as water was naturally playing a large role in sculpting out the physical shapes of the caves, as well as making the calcium accumulation inside for thousands and thousands of years.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The original display of the cave space that the piece is representing already has its own complexity with both strong aspects of the natural formation and human involvement. In one hand, the Karst caves are a display of long period of time all in one setting. The formation of the rocks took much longer than any average civilization let alone human\'s lifespan. In the other hand, the caves are often lit up by the highly artificial and saturated decorative lights. A decision made by the tourist department for groups of explorers to see better the breathtaking rock forms.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In recent years, according to more research done on the conditions of the Karst caves, some of them are being utilized by the Chinese government to host the ever growing big data hardware due to its controlled environment and many other safety factors. While more and more personal data are being stored by national scaled arrangements right inside of the mountains of Fu\'s hometown, she felt that it is time to recreate her strong childhood memories of the caves. She recreated the cave in a digital VR space for more people to explore and to bring attention into the multi-layered digital nature of our contemporary human life. The spacial sound placed in the digital cave echoes in between the nature like sounds in the cave as well as the hypothetical machine\'s operating noises. The experience in the digital cave also attempt to embody the concept of the Platos cave in the medium of virtually contracted realm, providing a contemplative environment for the visitor to wonder: walking, and teleporting within the control of the wireframed virtual hands that are given to them inside of the Karst caves.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Continue to her digital art practice, Fu creates virtual reality piece exploring the idea of the techno sublime, relating to Chinese and Western landscape paintings, as well as the technological culture changing the way humans live in the contemporary technological culture.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://snowyunxuefu.com/section/470931-Karst-VR.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://snowyunxuefu.com/section/470931-Karst-VR.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/288098672\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/288098672\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Snow Yunxue Fu is a Chinese-born and Chicago-based artist exploring the aesthetic concept of the sublime through a wide range of digital media.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fu has exhibited her work nationally and internationally, including Thoma Foundation Art House in Santa Fe; Venice Architectural Biennial; Current Museum of Art in New York; Hong Kong Arts Center, HK; ISEA 2016, HK; Expo Chicago, US; Digital Culture Center, MX; Kunsthalle Detroit Museum of Contemporary Art, US; NURTUREart Gallery, US; Gallery C Space, CN; West Village Art Gallery, CN; SIMULTAN Festival, RO; 9:16 Film Festival, AU; Spaces Gallery, Cleveland OH; Gene Siskel Film Center, Chicago IL; Supernova Digital Animation Festival, Detroit CO; International Mykonos Multimudia Festival, SOPERNOVA Digital Animation Festival, Denver CO; Greece; Galerie Protg, NY, and etc. She has presented her work and research in institutions, symposiums, and conferences internationally, and has given artist talks at the Elmhurst Art Museum, US; Chicago Artist Coalition, US; Lido Art Center, CN; Guizhou Minzu (Nationalities) University in Guiyang, CN; Celebrating Women in New Media Symposium at SAIC, US; Trans-National Identity Symposium, US; and Ox-bow School of Art and Artist\'s Residency, MI, US. Her early painting work, Kissing the Mother, is in the permanent collection of the National Museum of China in 1994, keeping the record of one of the youngest artists in the collection.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fu teaches mainly at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago (SAIC) in the Film, Video, New Media, and Animation Department, the Continuing Studies Department, and the Ox-bow School of Art and Artist Residency.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Karst','','publish','closed','open','','karst','','\nhttps://vimeo.com/288098672','2018-12-07 16:27:04','2018-12-07 16:27:04','',0,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/?p=211',0,'post','',0),(197,1,'2018-12-05 04:25:15','2018-12-05 04:25:15','','Lisa Moren, Neja Tomsic, Martin Baraga and Jaimes Mayhew 4','','inherit','closed','closed','','lisa-moren-neja-tomsic-martin-baraga-and-jaimes-mayhew-4-2','','','2018-12-05 04:25:15','2018-12-05 04:25:15','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Lisa-Moren-Neja-Tomsic-Martin-Baraga-and-Jaimes-Mayhew-4-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(198,1,'2018-12-05 04:25:25','2018-12-05 04:25:25','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://lisamoren.com/\">Lisa Moren</a>, <a href=\"http://www.ne-ja.com/\">Neja Tomsic</a>, <a href=\"http://www.baraga.net/\">Martin Baraga</a> and <a href=\"http://www.enginesofthefuture.com/\">Jaimes Mayhew</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"191,192,195,197\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"NONUMENT 01:: McKeldin Fountain is Baltimores virtual monument located in the Inner Harbor and free speech zone.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In opposition to bronze and stone, the nonument or no monument recreates the destroyed Brutalist-style monument the City of Baltimore and private partners tore down in January 2017. installs new and emerging media forms in order to capture the transitory significance of everyday experiences. We seek to honor hidden urban spaces that carry symbolic value for ordinary people.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By using this app, anyone can put back the fountain and experience first-hand memories from ordinary activities, art events and protests, including uprisings following the death of Freddie Gray, Peace Vigils, LGBTQ issues and Occupy Baltimore.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When viewers hold up a mobile device like a protest sign, the participant will put back the fountain with 18 animated waterfalls including an infamous double waterfall. Viewers will see and hear documented interviews that includes a diversity of Baltimore voices from a former Mayor and ACLU lawyer to rappers, teachers and protestors, including the Women In Black who stood for peace at the site every Friday since December 2001. Whisper Chambers inside the fountain offer underrepresented voices in Baltimore City that are often unheard but significant to the vibrant life of any urban environment.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The story of McKeldin Fountain is part of the escalating privatization of public spaces worldwide, a trend that continues to diminish access to full participation and free speech for ordinary people in everyday urban life. This socially engaged intervention is an ambitious take on the latest AR technology in order to address the politics of reclaiming public space including: how public behavior is controlled by a variety of mechanisms? and, who has more exclusive access to what spaces?&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This augmented reality public art project is free to download to your phone.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://nonument01.org\">http://nonument01.org</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/303771421\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/303771421\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Artists :: Lisa Moren, Director and Lead Production; Jaimes Mayhew, Co-Production;&nbsp;<br>Martin Bricelj Baraga and Neja Tomi, NONUMENT founders.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Software coding and app development by Balti-Virtual&nbsp;<br>Sound Score by Erik Spangler with Whisper Chambers by JMoney fur&nbsp;<br>Interviews by Lisa Moren&nbsp;<br>Interview editing by Jaimes Mayhew with audio engineering by Lexie Mountain&nbsp;<br>Artist Audio Tour by Lisa Moren with audio engineering by Timothy Nohe&nbsp;<br>3D models by Ben Shaffer, and by Ryan Zuber, IRC at UMBC.&nbsp;<br>The 3D printed model was printed by the good folks at the Digital Harbor Foundation.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This project grateful for the generous support from the Saul Zaentz Innovation Fund in Film + Media at Johns Hopkins University.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We are also grateful for support from The Andy Warhol Foundation for The Visual Arts, The Grit Fund, Baltimore Women and Tech, and the Imaging Research Center and CAHSSat UMBC.&nbsp;<br>Special thanks to for the expertise of Audrey Ewall, Fred Scharmen, Mike Schector and the Saul Zaentz Incubation Team. We appreciate the dedicated support from MoTA Museum, Baltimore Visitors Center, D-Center and Maryland Art Place who support this project in so many flexible ways.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','NONUMENT 01::McKeldin Fountain','','inherit','closed','closed','','184-revision-v1','','','2018-12-05 04:25:25','2018-12-05 04:25:25','',184,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/184-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(199,12,'2018-12-05 04:31:02','2018-12-05 04:31:02','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://taezoo.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"Taezoo Park (opens in a new tab)\">Taezoo Park</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"201,202,203,204,205,206\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Humans have developed technology hoping to live safe&nbsp;and healthy lives. Consequentially, we are surrounded by what we have madea new environment for a new creature, \"Digital Being.\"&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Digital Being is an invisible and formless creature born from discarded and forgotten technologies. It reveals itself through atypical movements or an interaction according to the machinery that it dominates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.taezoo.com/digital-being\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.taezoo.com/digital-being</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/85416800\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/85416800\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Taezoo Park has been making artwork out of abandoned technology combined with digital code to bring to life an imagined unknown creature from inside machines. He calls this new life Digital Being.\" He has been working on finding and depicting <g class=\"gr_ gr_10 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Grammar multiReplace\" id=\"10\" data-gr-id=\"10\">these creature</g> as a <g class=\"gr_ gr_5 gr-alert gr_spell gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim ContextualSpelling ins-del multiReplace\" id=\"5\" data-gr-id=\"5\">digitalogist</g>, new media artist, and maker in New York City for the past 10 years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Digital Being','','publish','closed','open','','digital-being','','\nhttps://vimeo.com/85416800','2018-12-07 16:27:26','2018-12-07 16:27:26','',0,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/?p=199',0,'post','',0),(201,1,'2018-12-05 04:27:31','2018-12-05 04:27:31','','Taezoo Park 6','','inherit','closed','closed','','taezoo-park-6','','','2018-12-05 04:27:31','2018-12-05 04:27:31','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Taezoo-Park-6.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(202,1,'2018-12-05 04:27:33','2018-12-05 04:27:33','','Taezoo Park 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','taezoo-park-1','','','2018-12-05 04:27:33','2018-12-05 04:27:33','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Taezoo-Park-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(203,1,'2018-12-05 04:27:36','2018-12-05 04:27:36','','Taezoo Park 2','','inherit','closed','closed','','taezoo-park-2','','','2018-12-05 04:27:36','2018-12-05 04:27:36','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Taezoo-Park-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(204,1,'2018-12-05 04:27:39','2018-12-05 04:27:39','','Taezoo Park 3','','inherit','closed','closed','','taezoo-park-3','','','2018-12-05 04:27:39','2018-12-05 04:27:39','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Taezoo-Park-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(205,1,'2018-12-05 04:27:42','2018-12-05 04:27:42','','Taezoo Park 4','','inherit','closed','closed','','taezoo-park-4','','','2018-12-05 04:27:42','2018-12-05 04:27:42','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Taezoo-Park-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(206,1,'2018-12-05 04:27:44','2018-12-05 04:27:44','','Taezoo Park 5','','inherit','closed','closed','','taezoo-park-5','','','2018-12-05 04:27:44','2018-12-05 04:27:44','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Taezoo-Park-5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(207,1,'2018-12-05 04:31:02','2018-12-05 04:31:02','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://taezoo.com/\">Taezoo Park</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"201,202,203,204,205,206\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Human has been developed technology hoping to live safely, healthfully, and eternally. Consequentially, we are surrounded by what we made, which is a new environment for a new creature, \"Digital Being.\"&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>DIGITAL BEING is an invisible and formless creature born from discarded and forgotten technologies. It reveals itself through an atypical movement or an interaction according to the machinery that it dominates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://www.taezoo.com/digital-being\">http://www.taezoo.com/digital-being</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/85416800\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/85416800\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Taezoo Park has been making artwork out of abandoned technology combined with digital code to bring to life an imagined unknown creature from inside machines. He calls this new life Digital Being\". He has been working on finding and depicting these creature as a digitalogist, new media artist, and maker in New York City for the past 10 years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Digital Being','','inherit','closed','closed','','199-revision-v1','','','2018-12-05 04:31:02','2018-12-05 04:31:02','',199,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/199-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(213,1,'2018-12-05 04:38:10','2018-12-05 04:38:10','','Snow Yunxue Fu 2','','inherit','closed','closed','','snow-yunxue-fu-2','','','2018-12-05 04:38:10','2018-12-05 04:38:10','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Snow-Yunxue-Fu-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(214,1,'2018-12-05 04:38:12','2018-12-05 04:38:12','','Snow Yunxue Fu 3','','inherit','closed','closed','','snow-yunxue-fu-3','','','2018-12-05 04:38:12','2018-12-05 04:38:12','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Snow-Yunxue-Fu-3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(215,1,'2018-12-05 04:38:14','2018-12-05 04:38:14','','Snow Yunxue Fu 4','','inherit','closed','closed','','snow-yunxue-fu-4','','','2018-12-05 04:38:14','2018-12-05 04:38:14','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Snow-Yunxue-Fu-4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(216,1,'2018-12-05 04:38:15','2018-12-05 04:38:15','','Snow Yunxue Fu 5','','inherit','closed','closed','','snow-yunxue-fu-5','','','2018-12-05 04:38:15','2018-12-05 04:38:15','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Snow-Yunxue-Fu-5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(217,1,'2018-12-05 04:38:17','2018-12-05 04:38:17','','Snow Yunxue Fu 6','','inherit','closed','closed','','snow-yunxue-fu-6','','','2018-12-05 04:38:17','2018-12-05 04:38:17','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Snow-Yunxue-Fu-6.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(218,1,'2018-12-05 04:43:13','2018-12-05 04:43:13','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"https://snowyunxuefu.com/\">Snow Yunxue Fu</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"212,213,214,215,216,217\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Karst is a liminal space in between the representational and the theatrical, the limited and the multi-dimensional, and the abstract and the real all meeting together.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Inspired from Fu\'s childhood experience visiting the caves from her hometown in Southwest China. The memories and the impact of the experience is still quite vivid. The space felt both extremely claustrophobic and large, and this aspect would be evident especially when the viewers are experiencing the piece within the VR Headset, as the ceiling of the cave is about 60 feet high (something you will definitely experience less in this recorded video). The rock shapes in the virtual scene are made with fluid simulation software Realflow, as water was naturally playing a large role in sculpting out the physical shapes of the caves, as well as making the calcium accumulation inside for thousands and thousands of years.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The original display of the cave space that the piece is representing already has its own complexity with both strong aspects of the natural formation and human involvement. In one hand, the Karst caves are a display of long period of time all in one setting. The formation of the rocks took much longer than any average civilization let alone human\'s lifespan. In the other hand, the caves are often lit up by the highly artificial and saturated decorative lights. A decision made by the tourist department for groups of explorers to see better the breathtaking rock forms.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In recent years, according to more research done on the conditions of the Karst caves, some of them are being utilized by the Chinese government to host the ever growing big data hardware due to its controlled environment and many other safety factors. While more and more personal data are being stored by national scaled arrangements right inside of the mountains of Fu\'s hometown, she felt that it is time to recreate her strong childhood memories of the caves. She recreated the cave in a digital VR space for more people to explore and to bring attention into the multi-layered digital nature of our contemporary human life. The spacial sound placed in the digital cave echoes in between the nature like sounds in the cave as well as the hypothetical machine\'s operating noises. The experience in the digital cave also attempt to embody the concept of the Platos cave in the medium of virtually contracted realm, providing a contemplative environment for the visitor to wonder: walking, and teleporting within the control of the wireframed virtual hands that are given to them inside of the Karst caves.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Continue to her digital art practice, Fu creates virtual reality piece exploring the idea of the techno sublime, relating to Chinese and Western landscape paintings, as well as the technological culture changing the way humans live in the contemporary technological culture.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://snowyunxuefu.com/section/470931-Karst-VR.html\">https://snowyunxuefu.com/section/470931-Karst-VR.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/288098672\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/288098672\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Snow Yunxue Fu is a Chinese-born and Chicago-based artist exploring the aesthetic concept of the sublime through a wide range of digital media.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fu has exhibited her work nationally and internationally, including Thoma Foundation Art House in Santa Fe; Venice Architectural Biennial; Current Museum of Art in New York; Hong Kong Arts Center, HK; ISEA 2016, HK; Expo Chicago, US; Digital Culture Center, MX; Kunsthalle Detroit Museum of Contemporary Art, US; NURTUREart Gallery, US; Gallery C Space, CN; West Village Art Gallery, CN; SIMULTAN Festival, RO; 9:16 Film Festival, AU; Spaces Gallery, Cleveland OH; Gene Siskel Film Center, Chicago IL; Supernova Digital Animation Festival, Detroit CO; International Mykonos Multimudia Festival, SOPERNOVA Digital Animation Festival, Denver CO; Greece; Galerie Protg, NY, and etc. She has presented her work and research in institutions, symposiums, and conferences internationally, and has given artist talks at the Elmhurst Art Museum, US; Chicago Artist Coalition, US; Lido Art Center, CN; Guizhou Minzu (Nationalities) University in Guiyang, CN; Celebrating Women in New Media Symposium at SAIC, US; Trans-National Identity Symposium, US; and Ox-bow School of Art and Artist\'s Residency, MI, US. Her early painting work, Kissing the Mother, is in the permanent collection of the National Museum of China in 1994, keeping the record of one of the youngest artists in the collection.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fu teaches mainly at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago (SAIC) in the Film, Video, New Media, and Animation Department, the Continuing Studies Department, and the Ox-bow School of Art and Artist Residency.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Karst','','inherit','closed','closed','','211-revision-v1','','','2018-12-05 04:43:13','2018-12-05 04:43:13','',211,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/211-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(219,1,'2018-12-05 04:45:52','2018-12-05 04:45:52','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://www.kairus.org/\">Andreas Zingerle and Linda Kronman</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery link=\"none\" ids=\"155,156,157,158\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Megacorp.\" is a corporate conglomerate inspired by its equally powerful counterparts in science fiction. The artwork is based on a collection of fake websites scraped from <g class=\"gr_ gr_12 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Grammar only-ins replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"12\" data-gr-id=\"12\">internet</g> by the artist duo KairUs. These companies exist only virtually and are used by cyber criminals for phishing attacks or to support scam stories. The \"Megacorp.\" exists therefore as an umbrella company for subsidiary companies that are 100% dummy cooperations. \"Megacorp.\" operates on a global scale and is constantly growing with firms represented in almost every branch of industry. The strategic objectives according to the \"Megacorp.\" <g class=\"gr_ gr_14 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Grammar only-ins doubleReplace replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"14\" data-gr-id=\"14\">Mission</g> statement is to: \"offer complete services from one source which can serve the entire market\". <g class=\"gr_ gr_15 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Punctuation only-ins replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"15\" data-gr-id=\"15\">Accordingly</g> the subsidiary companies cover domestic and international export, real estate agents, insurance companies, law firms, security companies, banks, educational institutions, hospitals, online commerce, economic communities <g class=\"gr_ gr_16 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Punctuation only-ins replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"16\" data-gr-id=\"16\">and</g> ministries<g class=\"gr_ gr_19 gr-alert gr_gramm gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim Style replaceWithoutSep\" id=\"19\" data-gr-id=\"19\">.The</g> functions of \"Megacorp.\" are presented in the form of an interim report and company visuals. By examining the fake websites the artwork reflects both the imaginary and the real world \'megacorps\', questioning centralization of power.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Written Document</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:file /-->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://megacorp.kairus.org\">http://megacorp.kairus.org</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/303156442\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/303156442\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>KairUs is a collective of two artists Linda Kronman (Finland) and Andreas Zingerle (Austria). Currently based in Daejeon (Republic of Korea), they explore topics such as vulnerabilities in IoT devices, corporatization of city governance in Smart Cities and citizen sensitive projects in which technology is used to reclaim control of our living environments. Their practice based research is closely intertwined with their artistic production, adopting methodologies used by anthropologists and sociologist, their artworks are often informed by archival research, participation observations and field research. Besides the artworks they publish academic research papers and open access publications to contextualize their artworks to wider discourses such as data privacy &amp; security, activism &amp; hacking culture, disruptive art practices, electronic waste and materiality of the internet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Tracking evil businesses   The Megacorp. Business conglomerate','','inherit','closed','closed','','154-revision-v1','','','2018-12-05 04:45:52','2018-12-05 04:45:52','',154,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/154-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(220,14,'2018-12-05 04:55:36','2018-12-05 04:55:36','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><a href=\"http://www.jingzhoustudio.net/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"Jing Zhou (opens in a new tab)\">Jing Zhou</a></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<p>[gallery ids=\"223,224\"]</p>\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Statement</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Through the Aleph\" is a net art project offering an unprecedented visual and interactive experience where many places on Earth and in space can be seen simultaneously in an instant. It visualizes the diversity of human civilizations (microcosm) and the unity of humanity without borders in the ever-changing universe (macrocosm); it draws the connections between individuals and the global environment, Earth and outer space, eternity and time, and art and science. With an unexpected approach to surveillance cameras and global networks this meditative web project uses live data to create an abstract landscape in an open source environment. It not only embraces the dream of peace on Earth but also explores the bond between humankind and nature through time and space in the present moment.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>* The project title was inspired by two great literary works\"The Aleph\" and \"Through the Looking-Glass.\" Perhaps the computer screen is our modern day looking-glass, and we are all Alice as we peer through our screens at an alternate reality.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Written Document</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:file {\"id\":221,\"href\":\"https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Jing-Zhou-Paper.pdf\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-file\"><a href=\"https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Jing-Zhou-Paper.pdf\">Jing Zhou - Paper</a><a href=\"https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Jing-Zhou-Paper.pdf\" class=\"wp-block-file__button\" download>Download</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:file -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Project Website<br></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://www.jingzhoustudio.net/projects/through_aleph/2019dec02.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"http://www.jingzhoustudio.net/projects/through_aleph/2019dec02.html (opens in a new tab)\">http://www.jingzhoustudio.net/projects/through_aleph/2019dec02.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Video Documentation</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/vimeo {\"url\":\"https://vimeo.com/303149487\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"vimeo\",\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://vimeo.com/303149487\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/vimeo -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Artist Bio</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Born in China, Jing Zhou is an interdisciplinary artist, designer, and professor in the US. Her <g class=\"gr_ gr_7 gr-alert gr_spell gr_inline_cards gr_run_anim ContextualSpelling ins-del multiReplace\" id=\"7\" data-gr-id=\"7\">award winning</g> work has been shown and collected internationally including: Triennale Design Museum, Milan; British Computer Society, London; Asian Cultural Center, New York City; SIGGRAPH Art Gallery; ISEA; CAA; Les Abattoirs Museum, France; Mons Memorial Museum, Belgium; Royal Institution of Australia; Athens Digital Art Festival, Greece;&nbsp;New York Hall of Science; Danish Poster Museum; GAMeC Modern and Contemporary Art Gallery, Italy; Taksim Republic Art Gallery, Istanbul; FILE, Sao Paulo; Sardinia Film Festival, Italy; Visual Information Design Assn. of Korea; Goethe Institute Alexandria, Egypt; Stanford University; Brown University; ArtCenter College of Design; Hungarian Electrographic Art Assn., Budapest; Grand Canyon National Park; PX3 Prix de la Photographie Paris Awards; International Photography Awards; public collection of the WRO Media Art Center, Poland; Moravian Gallery in Brno, Czech Republic; Waikato Museum, New Zealand; SDAI Museum of the Living Artist, San Diego; and Chinese Culture Center of San Francisco. Numerous books and magazines such as \"Photo Techniques,\" \"NMEDIAC,\" and \"Computer Graphics World\" have published her work. Jing is also a Gold Medal recipient of the Art Directors Club of New Jersey, Gold Winner of the American Design Awards, Silver Winner of the Summit International Creative Awards, and Prize Winner of IFUW (GWI) Poster Competition in Geneva.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Through the Aleph: A Glimpse of the World in Real Time','','publish','closed','open','','through-the-aleph-a-glimpse-of-the-world-in-real-time','','\nhttps://vimeo.com/303149487','2018-12-07 16:26:43','2018-12-07 16:26:43','',0,'https://urgency-reality.siggraph.org/wp/?p=220',0,'post','',0),(221,1,'2018-12-05 04: